<PageLayout
  title="The melanocortin system"
  kicker="Overview pillar"
  description="A single precursor protein, POMC, cleaved into the peptides that govern pigmentation, the stress axis, appetite, and inflammation."
  status="In development — full article in progress"
>
  <p>
    Pro-opiomelanocortin (POMC) is one of biology's most economical signalling
    arrangements: a single precursor protein that tissue-specific enzymes cleave
    into a family of melanocortin peptides — α-, β-, and γ-MSH and ACTH — each
    acting on its own subset of five G-protein-coupled receptors.
  </p>
  <p>This pillar page will cover:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>POMC processing — how prohormone convertases produce different peptides in the pituitary, hypothalamus, and skin.</li>
    <li>The melanocortin peptides and their relative receptor affinities.</li>
    <li>The endogenous antagonists — agouti and AgRP — and why inverse agonism matters here.</li>
    <li>How the same system reaches pigmentation, the HPA axis, energy balance, and inflammation.</li>
    <li>Links down into each of the five receptor pages.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Until the full article is reviewed and published, start with the
    <a href="/receptors">receptor overview</a>.
  </p>
</PageLayout>
